	== Lilly's Assembler (LAS) ==

LAS is a macro engine for the use of assembly programs. This document aims to
describe reasonably accurately the intended function of that engine and its
inbuilt macros. Below is a simple example:

	; For the 8086, similar to the following
	; mov ax, 0x0E48
	; int 0x10
	; inc ax
	; int 0x10
	; Would print 'HI' to the legacy BIOS terminal if formatted as a
	; boot sector.
	
	\\ldi[B8] ; load 16 bit immediate into accumulator
	\\inc[40] ; increment accumulator
	\\int[CD] ; software interrupt
	
	\ldi[0E48]
	\int[10]
	\inc
	\int[10]

	== Input Output ==

LAS does I/O through four routines: peek, consume, outc, and outs. Input and
output are arranged as a series of buffers sat upon a stack. The bottom of the
input stack reads from stdin while the bottom of the output stack is written
to stdout by the end of the program.

Peek reads one character from the top of the input stack, in the case that the
top of the input stack is empty, it is removed seamlessly and the character is
taken from the new top of the stack, if the bottom of the stack is removed,
then the character returned is ASCII NUL (0x00). Consume removes the character
that would be peeked from the top of the input stack. To be clear, peek reads
a character while consume removes it.

Outc pushes one character to the top of the output stack, while outs pushes
a given memory to the top of the output stack.

	== Base syntax ==

LAS is built primarily of two forms: byte lists and macro invokations.

Byte lists are formatted as a series of hexadecimal numbers enclosed in square
brackets ('[]'), these numbers are to be a power of two in length, and less
than 16 characters in length. Upon execution the byte list each byte shall be
outputted to the topmost output buffer. A byte list may include a macro.

Macro invokations begin with '\' and are followed by an identifier. An
identifier is defined by either a single one of the following characters:
"~!@#$%^&*()`-=+[]{}\|:;'<>,./?", double quotes, or any number of alphabetic
characters. Upon being read, a macro invokation shall be executed according to
its definition, which may either be a builtin macro (spoken of later) or a
user defined macro.

	== Builtin Macros ==

LAS has the following builtin macros:

	null:	Equivalent to `[ 00 ]'
	\:	Defines a macro. It is to be followed by the macro identifier
		and then either a byte list or some text enclosed in '{' '}'.
		In the case a byte list is used, it will be executed upon
		definition and the result instantiated upon the macro
		invokation. Otherwise, if it is scoped text, that text shall be
		copied to a buffer, immediate macros being invoked as they are
		encountered, that buffer is executed at macro invokation. If
		the macro identifier is followed by '*' (before the macro
		contents) the macro is considered immediate.
	*:	An immediate macro which is followed by a macro invokation
		which shall be run as though it is immediate.

	== Examples ==

Byte list usage:

	[ 12345678 ]
	; compiles to the following bytes in the following order:
	; 78 56 34 12

Byte list macro definition and use:

	\\var[ DE AD BE EF ]
	\\result[ 12345678 \var ]
	\result
	; compiles to the following result:
	; 78 56 34 12 DE AD BE EF

String macro definition and use:

	\\dead{[DE AD]}
	\\beef{[BE EF]}
	\\deadbeef{\dead\beef}
	\deadbeef
	; compiles to the following result:
	; DE AD BE EF

Immediate macro use:

	\\imm*{[DE AD]}
	\\macro{\imm}
	\\imm{[BE EF]}
	\macro\imm ; compiles to: DE AD BE EF

Use of the * macro:
	\\imm{[DE AD]}
	\\macro{\*\imm}
	\\imm{[BE EF]}
	\macro\imm ; compiles to: DE AD BE EF
